top250.codes <- top250.page[grep("title/tt", top250.page)]
#grep finds all the indices of lines of top250.page that have code containing "title/tt" which is where the movie codes we're interested in are stored
#those indices are used to store only those lines of top250.page containing those movie codes within top250.codes

top250.codes <- unlist(strsplit(top250.codes, split = "/"))[seq(from = 3, to = 1999, by = 4)]

#unlist then makes it so it's a vecotr rather than a list again so we can manipulate it more easily
#Then only using sequence, only every 4th entry starting at 3 is taken, and stored in top250.codes.  These are the entries where those codes are stored
#Only problem is the first entry is not related to a movie, and after that each code is repeated

1.b.

get.stuff <- function(imdb.code) {
  # Make the movie's main page address
  address <- paste("http://www.imdb.com/title/", imdb.code, sep = "")
  # Read the .html for the page
  page <- readLines(address)
  
  
  # extract the line that has the movie title and the year
  title.year <- page[grep("<title>", page)]
  #splits off all unnecessary characters using strsplit, stores the 2nd element which is the title within Title, and stores the 3rd element which is year within Year
  title.year <- unlist(strsplit(title.year, split="<title>"))
  title.year <- unlist(strsplit(title.year, split=" \\("))
  title.year <- unlist(strsplit(title.year, split="\\)"))
  Title <- title.year[2]
  Year <- as.numeric(title.year[3])
  

  # get content rating line using grep, uses strsplit to get rid of unnecessary characters
  Content.Rating <- page[grep("contentRating", page)[1]]
  Content.Rating <- unlist(strsplit(Content.Rating, split = ">"))[2]


  # get lines for user ratings and number of raters using grep
  # isolates the ratings and number of raters (separately) using strsplit
  # for num raters, uses gsub to get rid of commas
  # uses as.numeric to convert each to numbers
  User.Rating <- page[grep("Users rated this", page)[1]]
  User.Rating <- strsplit(User.Rating, "/")[[1]][1]
  User.Rating <- as.numeric(strsplit(User.Rating, "this ")[[1]][2])
  
  Num.Raters <- page[grep("Users rated this", page)[1]]
  Num.Raters <- strsplit(Num.Raters, " votes")[[1]][1]
  Num.Raters <- strsplit(Num.Raters, "\\(")[[1]][2]
  Num.Raters <- as.numeric(gsub("\\,", "", Num.Raters))

  
  
  
  # Get genre information line using grep
  # uses strsplit to isolate the genre type
  # paste puts together the different genre words together separated by a space
  inds <- grep("ref_=tt_stry_gnr", page)
  Genre <- unlist(strsplit(page[inds], "/genre/"))[seq(from = 2, to = length(inds)*2, by = 2)]
  Genre <- unlist(strsplit(Genre, "\\?"))[seq(from = 1, to = length(inds) *2, by = 2)]
  Genre <- paste(Genre, collapse = " ")
  
  
  
  # Make the movie's finance page address, stores the html in business.page
  address <- paste("http://www.imdb.com/title/", imdb.code, "/business", sep = "")
  business.page <- readLines(address)
  budget <- NA
  opening <- NA
  gross <- NA
  
  #Gets the line number with "Budget" and stores this in temp
  #If there is no budget, this is blank so budget is left as NA which was declared above
  #If there is a budget, then the line that has it is the line below temp (temp + 1) which is stored in budget
  #strsplit is used to isolate the budget number
  #Commas are removed using gsub
  #The number is then converted to a number using as.numeric
  #This is repeated for Opening and Gross
  temp <- grep("Budget", business.page)
  if (length(temp) > 0) {
    budget <- business.page[temp + 1]
    budget <- strsplit(budget, " \\(")[[1]][1]
    budget <- gsub("\\$", "", budget)
    budget <- as.numeric(gsub("\\,", "", budget))
  }
  
  temp <- grep("Opening", business.page)
  if (length(temp) > 0) {
    opening <- business.page[temp + 1]
    opening <- strsplit(opening, " \\(")[[1]][1]
    opening <- gsub("\\$", "", opening)
    opening <- as.numeric(gsub("\\,", "", opening))
  }
  
  temp <- grep("Gross", business.page)
  if (length(temp) > 0) {
    gross <- business.page[temp + 1]
    gross <- strsplit(gross, " \\(")[[1]][1]
    gross <- gsub("\\$", "", gross)
    gross <- as.numeric(gsub("\\,", "", gross))
  }
  
  
  # All of the above variables are returned in a list
  return(list(Title = Title, Year = Year, Content.Rating = Content.Rating,
              User.Rating = User.Rating, Num.Raters = Num.Raters, Genre = Genre, Budget = budget,
              Opening = opening, Gross = gross))
}

#Creates a function that finds the top x grossing movies where x is the input. Sorts them using order() based on their Gross so it is decreasing.  Then takes the first x rows of that ordered data.frame and only the 1st column (title) and 9th column (gross) and returns that.  
TopGrossing <- function(x, movieData = movies) {
  OrderedbyGross <- movieData[order(movieData$Gross, decreasing = TRUE),]
  if(x==1) {
    TopGrossing <- OrderedbyGross[x,c(1,9)]
  }
  else {
    TopGrossing <- OrderedbyGross[1:x,c(1,9)]
  }
  return(TopGrossing)
}

3.a.

linked.movies <- function(imdb.code) {
  # read the movie page
  address <- paste("http://www.imdb.com/title/", imdb.code, sep = "")

  page <- readLines(address)
  # find the lines with the recommendations and strip the unneeded stuff
  recs <- page[grep("rec_item", page)]
  recs <- unlist(strsplit(recs, "data-tconst="))[seq(from = 2, to = 24, by = 2)]
  # return the codes
  recs <- paste("tt", gsub("[^0-9]", "", recs), sep = "")
  return(recs)
}
linked.movies("tt0245429")

findlinks <- function(codes = top250.codes, moviedata = movies){
  #creates a blank matrix filled with 0's and 250 rows and 250 columns
  #Labels rows and columns according to the movie titles using colnames() and rownames()
  linkmatrix <- matrix(0, nrow = 250, ncol=250)
  colnames(linkmatrix) <- moviedata$Title
  rownames(linkmatrix) <- moviedata$Title

  #For every movie row i, gets the code for that movie and uses linked.movies to find all the linked movies for that particular movie, stores this in linked.  Then goes through every movie column j and checks if that corresponding element within the code vector is contained in linked then 1 is added to the ith row and jth column (where it would have been 0 before), otherwise it is left as 0.  This is done for every row and every column.  
  for(i in 1:250){
    linked <- linked.movies(codes[i])
  
    for(j in 1:250){
      if(is.element(codes[j],linked)){
        linkmatrix[i,j] <- linkmatrix[i,j] + 1
      }
    }
    
  }
  return(linkmatrix)
}

links1 <- findlinks()

3.b.

findlinks <- function(codes = top250.codes, moviedata = movies){
  linkmatrix <- matrix(0, nrow = 250, ncol=250)
  colnames(linkmatrix) <- moviedata$Title
  rownames(linkmatrix) <- moviedata$Title
  
  return(findlinksrec(linkmatrix, codes, 1))

}

findlinksrec <- function(linkmatrix, codes, i){
  if(i<251){
    linked <- linked.movies(codes[i])
    linkmatrix <- findlinksrec2(linkmatrix, codes, linked, i, 1)
    i = i + 1
    return(findlinksrec(linkmatrix, codes, i))
  }
  return(linkmatrix)
}

findlinksrec2 <- function(linkmatrix, codes, linked, i, j){
  if(j<251){
    if(is.element(codes[j],linked)){
      linkmatrix[i,j] <- linkmatrix[i,j] + 1
    }
    j = j + 1
    return(findlinksrec2(linkmatrix, codes, linked, i, j))
  }
  return(linkmatrix)
}

links2 <- findlinks()

3.c.

findtoplinks <- function(recs, codes = top250.codes, moviedata = movies){
  #creates a blank matrix filled with 0's and 250 rows and 250 columns
  #Labels rows and columns according to the movie titles using colnames() and rownames()
  linkmatrix <- matrix(0, nrow = 250, ncol=250)
  colnames(linkmatrix) <- moviedata$Title
  rownames(linkmatrix) <- moviedata$Title
  
  
    #For every movie row i, gets the code for that movie and uses linked.movies to find all the linked movies for that particular movie, stores this in linked.  Then goes through every movie column j and checks if that corresponding element within the code vector is contained in the first recs (input corresponding to number of top recommended movies to compare) values of linked then 1 is added to the ith row and jth column (where it would have been 0 before), otherwise it is left as 0.  This is done for every row and every column.  
  for(i in 1:250){
    linked <- linked.movies(codes[i])
    
    for(j in 1:250){
      if(is.element(codes[j],linked[1:recs])){
        linkmatrix[i,j] <- linkmatrix[i,j] + 1
      }
    }
    
  }
  return(linkmatrix)
}

toplinks <- findtoplinks(1)
